{"title_page": "Charles James Fox (editor)", "text_new": "'''Charles James Fox''' BA (c. 1827 \u2013 14 March 1903) was a newspaper editor and owner in Australia.\n\n==History==\nLittle is known of his earlier life, but he was brought up as a Roman Catholic and graduated BA from [[St John's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207718251 |title=General News |newspaper=[[The Express and Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=15 January 1870 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe emigrated to Adelaide, South Australia,{{when}} and married Mary Ann Toole on 31 October 1866.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article77132998 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[The Border Watch]] |location=South Australia |date=3 November 1866 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe was Latin master at [[John Lorenzo Young]]'s [[Adelaide Educational Institution]] from 1868<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207677000 |title=Adelaide Educational Institution |newspaper=[[The Express and Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=3 October 1868 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> to 1871<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158948072 |title=Examinations |newspaper=[[The Adelaide Observer]] |location=South Australia |date=23 December 1871 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=11 |via=Trove }}</ref> or later.\n\nFox was involved in various Catholic lay organizations: he was hon. sec. of the committee to erect a memorial to Fr. [[Johann Nepomucene Hinter\u00f6cker|J. N. Hinterocker]] SJ (c. 1820\u20131872)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28689568 |title=Topics of the Day |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |location=South Australia |date=19 October 1872 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }} Hinterocker and Julian Tenison Woods were both noted as scientist-priests.</ref>\nHe succeeded [[Benjamin Hoare]] as editor of ''[[The Irish Harp and Farmers' Herald]]'' in Jamuary 1870.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158940250 |title=The Week's News |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |location=South Australia |date=22 January 1870 |access-date=27 April 2020 |page=7 |via=Trove }}</ref> \nin which paper he notably criticised [[Laurence Sheil|Bishop Sheil]]'s excommunication of [[Mary MacKillop]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224362588 |title=The Bishop and the Sisters of Saint Joseph |newspaper=[[The Irish Harp and Farmers' Herald]] |location=South Australia |date=7 October 1871 |access-date=25 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }} Fox was one of many who consistently misspelled the bishop's name as \"Shiel\".</ref> and was ousted from the South Australian Catholic Association, of which he was president.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207700123 |title=General News |newspaper=[[The Express and Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=19 October 1871 |access-date=25 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> and founding member.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224541386 |title=SA Catholic Association |newspaper=[[The Irish Harp and Farmers' Herald]] |location=South Australia |date=5 November 1870 |access-date=27 April 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref>\nHe retired as editor around August 1875.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224368200 |title=Topics |newspaper=[[The Harp and Southern Cross]] |location=South Australia |date=5 November 1875 |access-date=27 April 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref> to concentrate on an agency he was running at 71 [[King William Street, Adelaide]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224368200 |title=Mr C. J. Fox |newspaper=[[The Harp and Southern Cross]] |location=South Australia |date=5 November 1875 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nIn 1883 he moved to Hobart, Tasmania, where he edited the ''[[Tasmanian Mail]]''. He left for New South Wales in June 1888<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article163542592 |title=Shipping |newspaper=[[Tasmanian News]] |location=Tasmania, Australia |date=20 June 1888 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=3 |via=Trove }}</ref> \n\nHe purchased the ''[[The Northern Argus (Narrabri)|Northern Argus]]'' of [[Narrabri, New South Wales]], which he ran as proprietor and editor. \nOn 29 August 1890 fire destroyed the building, owned by a Mr. Spencer, and its contents, all of which were owned by Fox: a steam engine and two presses, good quality type and consumables.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18994612 |title=Burning of e Newspaper Office at Narrabri. |newspaper=[[The Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=2 September 1890 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=7 |via=Trove }}</ref> Despite rumors, an inquest found no evidence of arson. Fox had a court case pending in which he was being sued for publishing a libel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71185570 |title=Narrabri Newspaper Case |newspaper=[[Australian Town and Country Journal]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=20 December 1890 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=14 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed editor of the \"funny and harmless old rag\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42940376 |title=Notes & Notices |newspaper=[[Morning Post (Cairns)]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=25 November 1899 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=3 |via=Trove }}</ref> the ''[[Cairns Argus]]'' in May 1899,<ref>{{cite news|title=Telegraphic News |date= 24 May 1899 |newspaper=The Northern Miner |location=Charters Towers, Queensland, Australia |page=3 |access-date=28 April 2020 |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article84868256 |via=Trove}}</ref> and was still editor in February 1903, when he sprained his ankle as the result of a fall and was hospitalised in [[Townsville]]. He died there a week later.\n\n[[Frank Fox (author)|Frank Fox]] (born 10 August 1874), author and editor of ''[[The Lone Hand (magazine)|The Lone Hand]]'' (and much else) was a son.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fox, Charles James}}\n[[Category:1827 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Australian Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "'''Charles James Fox''' BA (c. 1827 \u2013 14 March 1903) was a newspaper editor and owner in Australia.\n\n==History==\nLittle is known of his earlier life, but he was brought up as a Roman Catholic and graduated BA from [[St John's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207718251 |title=General News |newspaper=[[The Express And Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=15 January 1870 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe emigrated to Adelaide, South Australia,{{when}} and married Mary Ann Toole on 31 October 1866.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article77132998 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[The Border Watch]] |location=South Australia |date=3 November 1866 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe was Latin master at [[John Lorenzo Young]]'s [[Adelaide Educational Institution]] from 1868<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207677000 |title=Adelaide Educational Institution |newspaper=[[The Express And Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=3 October 1868 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> to 1871<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158948072 |title=Examinations |newspaper=[[The Adelaide Observer]] |location=South Australia |date=23 December 1871 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=11 |via=Trove }}</ref> or later.\n\nFox was involved in various Catholic lay organizations: he was hon. sec. of the committee to erect a memorial to Fr. [[Johann Nepomucene Hinter\u00f6cker|J. N. Hinterocker]] SJ (c. 1820\